# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: idris-lang
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] In computer science and logic, a **dependent type** is a type whose definition depends on a value.
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] It is an overlapping feature of type theory and type systems.
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] In intuitionistic type theory, dependent types are used to encode logic's quantifiers like "for all" and "there exists".
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] In functional programming languages like Agda, ATS, Rocq (previously known as *Coq*), F*, Epigram, Idris, and Lean, dependent types help reduce bugs by enabling the programmer to assign types that further restrain the set of possible implementations.
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] Two common examples of dependent types are *dependent functions* and *dependent pairs*.
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] The return type of a dependent function may depend on the *value* (not just type) of one of its arguments.
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] For instance, a function that takes a positive integer n may return an array of length n , where the array length is part of the type of the array.
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] (Note that this is different from polymorphism and generic programming, both of which include the type as an argument.) A dependent pair may have a second value, the type of which depends on the first value.
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] Sticking with the array example, a dependent pair may be used to pair an array with its length in a type-safe way.
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] Dependent types add complexity to a type system.
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] Deciding the equality of dependent types in a program may require computations.
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] In 1934, Haskell Curry noticed that the types used in typed lambda calculus, and in its combinatory logic counterpart, followed the same pattern as axioms in propositional logic.
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] Going further, for every proof in the logic, there was a matching function (term) in the programming language.
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] One of Curry's examples was the correspondence between simply typed lambda calculus and intuitionistic logic.
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] Predicate logic is an extension of propositional logic, adding quantifiers.
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] Howard and de Bruijn extended lambda calculus to match this more powerful logic by creating types for dependent functions, which correspond to "for all", and dependent pairs, which correspond to "there exists".
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] Because of this, and other work by Howard, propositions-as-types is known as the Curry–Howard correspondence.
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] In dependent type theory, a dependent type is a type whose specification may vary with a value, and can be viewed as analogous to an indexed family of sets.
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] Let ${\mathcal {U}}$ denote a universe of types, and write $A:{\mathcal {U}}$ to indicate that A is a type in ${\mathcal {U}}$ .
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] A dependent **family of types** over A is written $B:A\to {\mathcal {U}}$ , meaning that to each term $a:A$ the family assigns a type $B(a):{\mathcal {U}}$ .
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] Thus, given $A:{\mathcal {U}}$ and $B:A\to {\mathcal {U}}$ , the expression $B(a)$ denotes a type that depends on the particular value a .
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] In standard terminology, this is described by saying that the type $B(a)$ varies with a .
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] A function whose type of return value varies with its argument (i.e. there is no fixed codomain) is a **dependent function** and the type of this function is called **dependent product type**, **pi-type** (**Π type**) or **dependent function type**.
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] From a family of types $B:A\to {\mathcal {U}}$ we may construct the type of dependent functions ${\textstyle \prod _{x:A}B(x)}$ , whose terms are functions that take a term $a:A$ and return a term in $B(a)$ .
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] For this example, the dependent function type is typically written as ${\textstyle \prod _{x:A}B(x)}$ or ${\textstyle \prod {(x:A)}B(x)}$ .
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] If $B:A\to {\mathcal {U}}$ is a constant function, the corresponding dependent product type is equivalent to an ordinary function type.
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] That is, ${\textstyle \prod _{x:A}B}$ is judgmentally equal to $A\to B$ when B does not depend on x .
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] The name 'Π-type' comes from the idea that these may be viewed as a Cartesian product of types. Π-types can also be understood as models of universal quantifiers.
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] For example, if we write $\operatorname {Vec} (\mathbb {R} ,n)$ for *n*-tuples of real numbers, then ${\textstyle \prod _{n:\mathbb {N} }\operatorname {Vec} (\mathbb {R} ,n)}$ would be the type of a function which, given a natural number n, returns a tuple of real numbers of size n.
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] The usual function space arises as a special case when the range type does not actually depend on the input.
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] E.g. ${\textstyle \prod _{n:\mathbb {N} }{\mathbb {R} }}$ is the type of functions from natural numbers to the real numbers, which is written as $\mathbb {N} \to \mathbb {R}$ in typed lambda calculus.
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] The dual of the dependent product type is the **dependent pair type**, **dependent sum type**, **sigma-type**, or (confusingly) **dependent product type**.
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] Sigma-types can also be understood as existential quantifiers.
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] Continuing the above example, if, in the universe of types ${\mathcal {U}}$ , there is a type $A:{\mathcal {U}}$ and a family of types $B:A\to {\mathcal {U}}$ , then there is a dependent pair type ${\textstyle \sum _{x:A}B(x)}$ .
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] The dependent pair type captures the idea of an ordered pair where the type of the second term is dependent on the value of the first.
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] If B is a constant function, then the dependent pair type becomes (is judgmentally equal to) the product type, that is, an ordinary Cartesian product $A\times B$ .
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] For a more concrete example, taking A to again be type of unsigned integers from 0 to 255, and $B(a)$ to again be equal to $X_{a}$ for 256 more arbitrary $X_{a}$ , then ${\textstyle \sum _{x:A}B(x)}$ devolves into the sum $X_{0}+X_{1}+X_{2}+\ldots +X_{253}+X_{254}+X_{255}$ .
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] Let $A:{\mathcal {U}}$ be some type, and let $B:A\to {\mathcal {U}}$ .
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] By the Curry–Howard correspondence, B can be interpreted as a logical predicate on terms of A .
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] For a given $a:A$ , whether the type $B(a)$ is inhabited indicates whether a satisfies this predicate.
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] The correspondence can be extended to existential quantification and dependent pairs: the proposition $\exists {a}{\in }A\,B(a)$ is true if and only if the type ${\textstyle \sum _{a:A}B(a)}$ is inhabited.
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] For example, $m:\mathbb {N}$ is less than or equal to $n:\mathbb {N}$ if and only if there exists another natural number $k:\mathbb {N}$ such that $m+k=n$ .
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] That is, a proof of the statement that m is less than or equal to n is a pair that contains both a non-negative number k , which is the difference between m and n , and a proof of the equality $m+k=n$ .
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] Henk Barendregt developed the lambda cube as a means of classifying type systems along three axes.
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] The eight corners of the resulting cube-shaped diagram each correspond to a type system, with simply typed lambda calculus in the least expressive corner, and calculus of constructions in the most expressive.
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] The three axes of the cube correspond to three different augmentations of the simply typed lambda calculus: the addition of dependent types, the addition of polymorphism, and the addition of higher kinded type constructors (functions from types to types, for example).
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] The lambda cube is generalized further by pure type systems.
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] The system $\lambda \Pi$ of pure first order dependent types, corresponding to the logical framework LF, is obtained by generalising the function space type of the simply typed lambda calculus to the dependent product type.
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] The system $\lambda \Pi 2$ of second order dependent types is obtained from $\lambda \Pi$ by allowing quantification over type constructors.
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] In this theory the dependent product operator subsumes both the $\to$ operator of simply typed lambda calculus and the $\forall$ binder of System F.
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] The higher order system $\lambda \Pi \omega$ extends $\lambda \Pi 2$ to all four forms of abstraction from the lambda cube: functions from terms to terms, types to types, terms to types and types to terms.
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] The system corresponds to the calculus of constructions whose derivative, the calculus of inductive constructions is the underlying system of Rocq.
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] The Curry–Howard correspondence implies that types can be constructed that express arbitrarily complex mathematical properties.
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] If the user can supply a constructive proof that a type is *inhabited* (i.e., that a value of that type exists) then a compiler can check the proof and convert it into executable computer code that computes the value by carrying out the construction.
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] The proof checking feature makes dependently typed languages closely related to proof assistants.
[src:idris-lang/dependent-type] The code-generation aspect provides a powerful approach to formal program verification and proof-carrying code, since the code is derived directly from a mechanically verified mathematical proof.
[src:idris-lang/documentation] Idris 2 is still a work in progress, but documentation continues to grow, and available from https://idris2.readthedocs.org.
[src:idris-lang/documentation] The community-maintained Idris2 tutorial (originally written by Stefan Höck for undergraduate university teaching) is an excellent entry-point.
[src:idris-lang/documentation] Some further resources are linked on the Idris2 GitHub Wiki.
[src:idris-lang/documentation] You can also find our Community Standards here.
[src:idris-lang/documentation] As such, documentation is no longer available through the website.
[src:idris-lang/documentation] If you still require access to the Idris 1 documentation, the following Internet Archive (aka.
[src:idris-lang/documentation] Additionally, the old Idris 1 Wiki contains a lot of community supplied information.
[src:idris-lang/idris-programming-language] The Idris type system is similar to Agda's.
[src:idris-lang/idris-programming-language] Compared to Agda, Idris prioritizes management of side effects and support for embedded domain-specific languages.
[src:idris-lang/idris-programming-language] Idris is compiled by modular backends, which provide code generation and a runtime system.
[src:idris-lang/idris-programming-language] The Idris compiler includes backends for Chez Scheme, Racket, JavaScript (both browser- and Node.js-based), and C.
[src:idris-lang/idris-programming-language] Additional third-party backends are available for other platforms.
[src:idris-lang/idris-programming-language] Idris is named after a singing dragon from the 1970s UK children's television programme *Ivor the Engine*.
[src:idris-lang/idris-programming-language] Idris combines a number of features from relatively mainstream functional programming languages with features borrowed from proof assistants.
[src:idris-lang/idris-programming-language] The syntax of Idris shows many similarities with that of Haskell.
[src:idris-lang/idris-programming-language] The only differences between this program and its Haskell equivalent are the single (instead of double) colon in the type signature of the main function, and the omission of the word "`where`" in the module declaration.
[src:idris-lang/idris-programming-language] Idris supports inductively-defined data types and parametric polymorphism.
[src:idris-lang/idris-programming-language] With dependent types, it is possible for values to appear in the types; in effect, any value-level computation can be performed during type checking.
[src:idris-lang/idris-programming-language] The function `append` appends a vector of `m` elements of type `a` to a vector of `n` elements of type `a`.
[src:idris-lang/idris-programming-language] Since the precise types of the input vectors depend on a value, it is possible to be certain at compile time that the resulting vector will have exactly (`n` + `m`) elements of type `a`.
[src:idris-lang/idris-programming-language] The word "`total`" invokes the totality checker which will report an error if the function doesn't cover all possible cases or cannot be (automatically) proven not to enter an infinite loop.
[src:idris-lang/idris-programming-language] `Num` a signifies that the type a belongs to the type class `Num`.
[src:idris-lang/idris-programming-language] Note that this function still typechecks successfully as total, even though there is no case matching `Nil` in one vector and a number in the other.
[src:idris-lang/idris-programming-language] Because the type system can prove that the vectors have the same length, we can be sure at compile time that case will not occur and there is no need to include that case in the function’s definition.
[src:idris-lang/idris-programming-language] Dependent types are powerful enough to encode most properties of programs, and an Idris program can prove invariants at compile time.
[src:idris-lang/idris-programming-language] This makes Idris into a proof assistant.
[src:idris-lang/idris-programming-language] There are two standard ways of interacting with proof assistants: by writing a series of tactic invocations (Rocq style), or by interactively elaborating a proof term (Epigram–Agda style).
[src:idris-lang/idris-programming-language] Idris supports both modes of interaction, although the set of available tactics is not yet as useful as that of Rocq.
[src:idris-lang/idris-programming-language] Because Idris contains a proof assistant, Idris programs can be written to pass proofs around.
[src:idris-lang/idris-programming-language] If treated naïvely, such proofs remain around at runtime.
[src:idris-lang/idris-programming-language] Idris aims to avoid this pitfall by aggressively erasing unused terms.
[src:idris-lang/idris-programming-language] By default, Idris generates native code through C.
[src:idris-lang/idris-programming-language] The other officially supported backend generates JavaScript.
[src:idris-lang/idris-programming-language] Idris 2 is a new self-hosted version of the language which deeply integrates a linear type system, based on quantitative type theory.
[src:idris-lang/purely-functional-programming] In computer science, **purely functional programming** usually designates a programming paradigm—a style of building the structure and elements of computer programs—that treats all computation as the evaluation of mathematical functions.
[src:idris-lang/purely-functional-programming] This style handles state changes without losing the referential transparency of the program expressions.
[src:idris-lang/purely-functional-programming] Purely functional programming consists of ensuring that functions, inside the functional paradigm, will only depend on their arguments, regardless of any global or local state.
[src:idris-lang/purely-functional-programming] A pure functional subroutine only has visibility of changes of state represented by state variables included in its scope.
[src:idris-lang/purely-functional-programming] The exact difference between pure and impure functional programming is a matter of controversy.
[src:idris-lang/purely-functional-programming] Sabry's proposed definition of purity is that all common evaluation strategies (call-by-name, call-by-value, and call-by-need) produce the same result, ignoring strategies that error or diverge.
[src:idris-lang/purely-functional-programming] A program is usually said to be functional when it uses some concepts of functional programming, such as first-class functions and higher-order functions.
[src:idris-lang/purely-functional-programming] However, a first-class function need not be purely functional, as it may use techniques from the imperative paradigm, such as arrays or input/output methods that use mutable cells, which update their state as side effects.
[src:idris-lang/purely-functional-programming] In fact, the earliest programming languages cited as being functional, IPL and Lisp, are both "impure" functional languages by Sabry's definition.
[src:idris-lang/purely-functional-programming] Each evaluation strategy which ends on a purely functional program returns the same result.
[src:idris-lang/purely-functional-programming] In particular, it ensures that the programmer does not have to consider in which order programs are evaluated, since eager evaluation will return the same result as lazy evaluation.
[src:idris-lang/purely-functional-programming] However, it is still possible that an eager evaluation may not terminate while the lazy evaluation of the same program halts.
[src:idris-lang/purely-functional-programming] An advantage of this is that lazy evaluation can be implemented much more easily; as all expressions will return the same result at any moment (regardless of program state), their evaluation can be delayed as much as necessary.
[src:idris-lang/purely-functional-programming] In a purely functional language, the only dependencies between computations are data dependencies, and computations are deterministic.
[src:idris-lang/purely-functional-programming] Therefore, to program in parallel, the programmer need only specify the pieces that should be computed in parallel, and the runtime can handle all other details such as distributing tasks to processors, managing synchronization and communication, and collecting garbage in parallel.
[src:idris-lang/purely-functional-programming] This style of programming avoids common issues such as race conditions and deadlocks, but has less control than an imperative language.
[src:idris-lang/purely-functional-programming] To ensure a speedup, the granularity of tasks must be carefully chosen to be neither too big nor too small.
[src:idris-lang/purely-functional-programming] In theory, it is possible to use runtime profiling and compile-time analysis to judge whether introducing parallelism will speed up the program, and thus automatically parallelize purely functional programs.
[src:idris-lang/purely-functional-programming] In practice, this has not been terribly successful, and fully automatic parallelization is not practical.
[src:idris-lang/purely-functional-programming] Purely functional data structures are persistent.
[src:idris-lang/purely-functional-programming] Persistency is required for functional programming; without it, the same computation could return different results.
[src:idris-lang/purely-functional-programming] Functional programming may use persistent non-purely functional data structures, while those data structures may not be used in purely functional programs.
[src:idris-lang/purely-functional-programming] Purely functional data structures are often represented in a different way than their imperative counterparts.
[src:idris-lang/purely-functional-programming] For example, array with constant-time access and update is a basic component of most imperative languages and many imperative data-structures, such as hash table and binary heap, are based on arrays.
[src:idris-lang/purely-functional-programming] Arrays can be replaced by map or random access list, which admits purely functional implementation, but the access and update time is logarithmic.
[src:idris-lang/purely-functional-programming] Therefore, purely functional data structures can be used in languages which are non-functional, but they may not be the most efficient tool available, especially if persistency is not required.
[src:idris-lang/purely-functional-programming] In general, conversion of an imperative program to a purely functional one also requires ensuring that the formerly-mutable structures are now explicitly returned from functions that update them, a program structure called store-passing style.
[src:idris-lang/purely-functional-programming] A purely functional language is a language which only admits purely functional programming.
[src:idris-lang/purely-functional-programming] Purely functional programs can however be written in languages which are not purely functional.
[src:idris-lang/www-idris-lang-org] Idris is a programming language designed to encourage *Type-Driven Development*.
[src:idris-lang/www-idris-lang-org] In type-driven development, types are tools for constructing programs.
[src:idris-lang/www-idris-lang-org] We treat the type as the *plan* for a program, and use the compiler and type checker as our assistant, guiding us to a complete program that satisfies the type.
[src:idris-lang/www-idris-lang-org] The more expressive the type is that we give up front, the more confidence we can have that the resulting program will be correct.
[src:idris-lang/www-idris-lang-org] In Idris, types are first-class constructs in the language.
[src:idris-lang/www-idris-lang-org] This means types can be passed as arguments to functions, and returned from functions just like any other value, such as numbers, strings, or lists.
[src:idris-lang/www-idris-lang-org] You can see some small examples, then take a look at the documentation.
[src:idris-lang/www-idris-lang-org] The Idris source is available from the Idris repository.
[src:idris-lang/www-idris-lang-org] There are some legacy tools and code available in the idris-hackers organisation.
[src:idris-lang/www-idris-lang-org] , with several channels for learning, help, and different aspects of development.
[src:idris-lang/www-idris-lang-org] This is probably the most active place for interactive discussion of Idris and projects using it.
[src:idris-lang/www-idris-lang-org] There is an Idris community on Discord with several channels for learning, help and different aspects of development.
[src:idris-lang/www-idris-lang-org] You can get an invitation to join here This is currently probably the most active place for interactive discussion of Idris.
[src:idris-lang/www-idris-lang-org] However, at the time of writing (2026-05-18), it is very rarely used.
[src:idris-lang/www-idris-lang-org] All participants in these forums are requested to abide by the community standards.
[src:idris-lang/www-idris-lang-org] Idris development is led by Edwin Brady at the School of Computer Science, University of St Andrews.
[src:idris-lang/www-idris-lang-org] Many thanks to Heath Johns for designing the logo.
